"Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1228–before 3 May 1275":"about 1228–before 3 May 1275","1226–Female":"1226–Deceased","1227–1269":"1227–1269","1227–1315":"1227–1315","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1194–1274":"1194–1274","–1307":"–1307","before 3 May 1275":"before 3 May 1275","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1269":"1269","about 1228":"about 1228","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1256":"about 1256","20 Apr 1274":"20 April 1274","1307":"1307","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ros","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Enrique, Luis, Jose, Alberto, Eduardo, Rafael, Elena, Fidel, Joaquin, Manuel, Pablo, Ramon.  Southeast Asian Leang, Phon, Lap, Phan, Pho, Saroeun, Sophal, Sophan, Sophea, Tha, Thang, Yen.","Catalan: nickname for someone with blond hair or a fair complexion, ultimately from Latin <i>russus</i>.","Swedish: ornamental name from <i>ros</i> ‘rose’."],"variants":[{"name":"Rus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Romanian Simion, Grigore, Doina, Dorel, Ilie, Liviu, Petru, Vasile.","Czech, Slovak, and Romanian (of Slavic origin): ethnic name for a Russian, ultimately derived from an Old Norse term meaning ‘oarsman, rower’ (from the root <i>roths-</i>), a reference to the fact that the Russian state was established by Scandinavians who rowed their ships up rivers inland from the Baltic sea. In some cases this may also be origin of the Slovenian and Croatian surname (see 3 below).","Czech: descriptive nickname from the adjective <i>rusý</i> ‘blond’."]},{"name":"Ross","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from one or other of a number of Scottish and English places called Ross or Roos(e), especially Roose (Lancashire) and Roos (East Yorkshire). The placenames derive from a British ancestor of Welsh <i>rhos</i> ‘moor, heath, plain’, which is the sense of the cognate Gaelic word <i>ros</i>. The Scottish surname has at least three origins. First, the Anglo-Norman family from Roos (East Yorkshire) was introduced to Scotland when Robert of Roos, lord of Wark Castle (Northumberland), married Isabella, an illegitimate daughter of King William the Lion. Second, various families took the name from the province of Ross in northern Scotland and other places of that name. Third, there were Norman families in Scotland by the 13th century who probably derived their name from Rots in Normandy (see 2 below). The descendants of Godfrey <i>de Ros</i>, tenant of the de Morville lords of Cunninghame, were major landholders in Ayrshire, and almost certainly took their name from Rots. The Rose family of Kilravock (Nairnshire) may take their name from either of these three (see   Rose  ). The lairds of Balnagown adopted the surname <i>Ross</i> after the earldom of Ross (to which they considered themselves rightful heirs) had passed into other hands through the female line.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Rots in Calvados (France), probably named with the ancient Germanic element <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’ (compare   Rhodes  ). This was the original home of a family de Ros, who were established in Kent in 1130 and had major estates in Kent until well into the 13th century.","English: habitational name from Wrose, in Shipley, near Bradford (Yorkshire), with re-spelling of <i>Wr-</i> as <i>R-</i> due to the loss of /w/ before /r/ in early modern English pronunciation. The spelling <i>Wrose</i> is no longer current. The placename derives from Old English <i>wrāse</i> ‘knot, something twisted’, referring to the steep-sided hill on which the settlement stands, with the sense ‘broken or twisting hill’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":31,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Ros of Wark III was born about 1228, in Wark, Northumberland, England as the son of Robert de Ros of Wark II and Margaret de Brus. He had at least 1 son with Christian Bertram. In 1234, at the age of 7, his occupation is listed as justice of the kings bench . He died before 3 May 1275, in Northumberland, England."},"et":{"about 1228–before 3 May 1275":"umbes 1228–enne 3. maid 1275","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","1227–1269":"1227–1269","1227–1315":"1227–1315","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1194–1274":"1194–1274","–1307":"–1307","before 3 May 1275":"enne 3. maid 1275","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1269":"1269","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1256":"umbes 1256","20 Apr 1274":"20. aprill 1274","1307":"1307","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1228–before 3 May 1275":"noin 1228–ennen vuotta 3. toukokuuta 1275","1226–Female":"1226–Kuollut","1227–1269":"1227–1269","1227–1315":"1227–1315","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1194–1274":"1194–1274","–1307":"–1307","before 3 May 1275":"ennen vuotta 3. toukokuuta 1275","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1269":"1269","about 1228":"noin 1228","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1256":"noin 1256","20 Apr 1274":"20. huhtikuuta 1274","1307":"1307","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"about 1228–before 3 May 1275":"environ 1228–avant 3 mai 1275","1226–Female":"1226–Décédée","1227–1269":"1227–1269","1227–1315":"1227–1315","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1194–1274":"1194–1274","–1307":"–1307","before 3 May 1275":"avant 3 mai 1275","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1269":"1269","about 1228":"environ 1228","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1256":"environ 1256","20 Apr 1274":"20 avril 1274","1307":"1307","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Angleterre","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Ros of Wark III est né environ 1228, à Wark, Northumberland, Angleterre, fils de Robert de Ros of Wark II et Margaret de Brus. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Christian Bertram. En 1234, à l’âge de 7 ans, sa profession de son indiquée est justice of the kings bench . Il est décédé avant 3 mai 1275, à Northumberland, Angleterre."},"de":{"about 1228–before 3 May 1275":"um 1228–vor 3. Mai 1275","1226–Female":"1226–Verstorben","1227–1269":"1227–1269","1227–1315":"1227–1315","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1245–1311":"1245–1311","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1194–1274":"1194–1274","–1307":"–1307","before 3 May 1275":"vor 3. Mai 1275","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1269":"1269","about 1228":"um 1228","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1256":"um 1256","20 Apr 1274":"20. April 1274","1307":"1307","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England","lifeSummary":"Robert de Ros of Wark III wurde